Yigdal elohim h/±ay veyishtabah/±, nimtza veÚeyn et el metziÚuto./PR
Eh/±ad veÚeyn yah/±id keyih/±udo, nelam vegam eyn sof leÚah/±duto./PR
Eyn lo demut haguf veÚeyno guf, lo naÚaroh/± elav kedushato./PR
Kadmon leh/±ol davar asher nivra, rishon veÚeyn reyshit/PR
lereyshito./PR
Hino adon olam veh/±ol notzar, yoreh gedulato umalh/±uto./PR
/UNShe/XXfa nevuÚato netano el, anshey segulato vetifar-to./PI/PR
/SCN/XXOTE/XX. /ITYigdal/XX was written by Daniel ben Judah, a fourteenth century poet.
He based it upon MaimonidesÚs Thirteen Articles of Faith. We have
attempted to make the closing line more acceptable to the contemporary
worshipper by referring to the sustenance of life, rather than resurrection
of the dead, as the true testimony of GodÚs blessing.    /SC/XXA.G./XX/PR
